#=GF CC   The OapA domain gets its name from the Haemophilus influenzae
#=GF CC   protein OapA, which is required for the expression of colony
#=GF CC   opacity, thus opacity- associated protein A [1]. The OapA
#=GF CC   protein is required for efficient nasopharyngeal mucosal
#=GF CC   colonization, and its expression is associated with a
#=GF CC   distinctive transparent colony phenotype. OapA is thought to be
#=GF CC   a secreted protein, and its expression exhibits high-frequency
#=GF CC   phase variation [1].  The OapA domain has been shown to bind to
#=GF CC   peptidoglycan in the E. coli protein YtfB [3]. A screen to
#=GF CC   identify factors that affect cell division in E. coli discovered
#=GF CC   that overproducing a fragment of YtfB, including its OapA
#=GF CC   domain, caused cells to grow as long filaments [3]. OapA domains
#=GF CC   are commonly associated with other domains that are involved in
#=GF CC   breaking peptidoglycan cross-links [4]. The OapA domain is
#=GF CC   distantly related to Pfam:PF01476.
